{"key":"processedPost-10788126","value":{"id":10788126,"first":10787425,"last":10794752,"when":1249265161,"utime":"08/03/09 05:06 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />steam is not what sterilizes, temperature is.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />Not so.<br /><br />250F in an oven is not even close to 250F via steam in a pressure cooker.<br /><br />Steam IS what sterilizes.&nbsp; A towel will conduct heat from the bags to the cool outside air in the kitchen or lab, defeating the purpose.&nbsp; It's important that steam completely surrounds the bags during the sterilization cycle to assure complete sterilization.&nbsp; Wad up foil, use jar lids, or get creative with spoons, etc., but make sure steam completely surrounds the bags.&nbsp; <br /><br />I don't see how proper autoclave bags could possibly melt from side contact unless you're using a gas stove and have the flame too high where it's wrapping around the edges.&nbsp; I've been using them since they first came out in the 80s and have never had a single bag melt on me.<br />RR","title":"Re: PC'er Vs. Oven","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}